-- Crude Oil Gains, Hog Futures, Cattle Fall: Commodities at Close
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2012-04-20T21:55:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-20/crude-oil-gains-hog-futures-cattle-fall-commodities-at-close.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of
24 commodities advanced 0.6 percent to 676.38. The UBS Bloomberg
CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials rose 0.5 percent to 1,565.063.  CRUDE OIL  Oil rose for the first time in three days as German
confidence data beat forecasts and strengthened the euro and
stock markets.  Futures gained 0.8 percent after the Munich-based Ifo
institute said today its business climate index, based on a
survey of 7,000 executives, climbed for a sixth month in April.
The euro advanced against the dollar and equities gained,
helping boosting dollar-denominated  oil prices .  Crude for May delivery rose 78 cents to settle at $103.05
barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . The May contract,
which rose 22 cents this week, expired at the close of floor
trading. The more actively traded June futures rose $1.16, or
1.1 percent, to $103.88 a barrel.  Brent oil for June settlement gained 76 cents, or 0.6
percent, to $118.76 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures
 Europe  exchange.  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures declined, marking the second straight weekly
drop, on speculation that U.S. pork demand is easing as supplies
increase. Cattle prices also fell.  U.S. commercial pork output in the first quarter rose 2.4
percent to 5.86 billion pounds (2.66 million metric tons) from a
year earlier, the Department of Agriculture said today. In
March, wholesale pork fell 5.8 percent, the sixth straight drop.  Hog futures for June settlement retreated 1.5 percent to
settle at 87.4 cents a pound on the  Chicago  Mercantile Exchange.
This week, the price dropped 3.1 percent, following the 3.5
percent slump last week.  Cattle futures for June delivery slid 0.3 percent to settle
at $1.1545 a pound on the CME.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement declined 0.1
percent to $1.55325 a pound in Chicago.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas futures climbed for the first time in four days
in New York on forecasts of cooler weather in the eastern half
of the U.S. that may boost demand for the heating fuel.  Gas gained 1 percent as MDA EarthSat Weather predicted
seasonal or below-normal temperatures in parts of the central
and eastern U.S. through April 24. Prices dropped to $1.907 per
million British thermal units yesterday, the lowest settlement
price since September 2001.  Natural gas for May delivery rose 2 cents to settle at
$1.927 per million British thermal units on the Nymex. The
futures have declined 55 percent from a year ago and dropped 2.7
percent this week.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline slid to a seven-week low in  New York  as Brent
crude’s premium narrowed versus the U.S. benchmark oil, making
some motor fuel less expensive to process.  Futures fell 0.4 percent, declining for a sixth straight
day. A weaker Brent compared with U.S. benchmark West Texas
Intermediate oil can reduce the cost of imports from Europe and
of fuel refined on the East and Gulf coasts, where refineries
process crude priced off Brent.  Gasoline for May delivery fell 1.14 cents to settle at
$3.1427 a gallon on the Nymex, the lowest settlement since Feb.
29. Prices fell 6.1 percent this week, the biggest weekly
decline since the seven days ended Sept. 23.  Heating oil for May delivery rose 1.25 cents, or 0.4
percent, to settle at $3.1376 a gallon on the exchange. Prices
fell 1.2 percent this week, the first loss in three weeks.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar futures fell, extending a slump to a 10-month low, on
signs of growing supplies from Asia and  Brazil , the world’s top
exporter. Coffee, cocoa, cotton and orange juice rose.  Raw sugar for July delivery dropped 1 percent to settle at
21.55 cents a pound on ICE Futures U.S. in New York.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery rose 1.9 percent
to $1.7895 a pound, and cocoa futures for July delivery gained
1.6 percent to $2,269 a metric ton in New York.  Cotton futures for July delivery added 0.3 percent to 91.01
cents a pound on ICE. Prices gained for a fourth day, the
longest rally since March 28.  Orange-juice futures for July delivery climbed 2.2 percent
to $1.5065 a pound, capping a weekly gain of 3.4 percent, the
first rally since early March.  GRAINS  Soybean futures surged to a seven-month high on signs that
smaller harvests in  South America  may lead to increased demand
for supplies from the U.S., the world’s biggest exporter. Corn
declined, capping a second weekly drop.  Soybean futures for July delivery rose 2 percent to close
at $14.495 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade.  Corn futures for July delivery slid 1.5 percent to $6.03 a
bushel on the CBOT, capping a 2.9 percent weekly decline.  Wheat dropped for the fourth time this week as the pace of
development quickened for plants that emerged from winter
dormancy because of favorable weather in the southern U.S. Great
Plains, bolstering prospects for yields.  Wheat futures for July delivery declined 1.1 percent to
settle at $6.23 a bushel on the CBOT. The price fell 1.2 percent
this week.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold futures rose for the second straight day as the
dollar’s decline spurred demand for the metal as an alternative
asset.  Gold futures for June delivery rose 0.1 percent to settle
at $1,642.80 an ounce on the Comex in New York.  Silver futures for July delivery fell 0.4 percent to $31.72
an ounce.  On the Nymex, palladium futures for June delivery advanced
2.1 percent to $676.90 an ounce.  Platinum futures for July delivery climbed 0.4 percent to
$1,584.20 an ounce.  BASE METALS  Copper rose to a one-week high in New York as global
inventories fell and the unexpected gain in German business
confidence boosted demand prospects.  Copper futures for July delivery climbed 1.9 percent to
settle at $3.7065 a pound on the Comex. Prices gained 2.2
percent this week.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months gained 1.8 percent to $8,192.50 a metric ton ($3.72 a
pound). Nickel, lead, zinc, aluminum and tin also rose in
London.  To contact the reporters on this story:
